<HEADLINE>
<P>
PRESIDENT CLINTON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With a cogent editorial ("You're President . . . and They're Not," Aug. 15), 
The Times has urged President Clinton to press on with his ambitious agenda 
despite a troublesome first two years. Emphasized are the President's enormous 
energy, intelligence and appetite for the big issues. 
</P>
<P>
 In contrast to the veto presidency of George Bush, here is a leader who has 
dared to engage the time-encrusted monsters of health care, crime, foreign 
trade (NAFTA), budgetary control, the environment and government waste. 
Notwithstanding his Administration's stumbling and Republican obstructionism at 
almost every turn, Clinton has set before the American people uncomfortable and 
unavoidable choices that will have profound impact on their lives. 
</P>
<P>
 Emerson has written, "People wish to be settled; only as far as they are 
unsettled is there any hope for them." Viewed from that perspective, the 
battle-scarred Clinton presidency gives us much to hope for in the next two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
 WILLIAM CORZINE 
</P>
<P>
 Hacienda Heights 
</P>
<P>
 * Your editorial is very well stated except that the culprits causing 
President Clinton problems are from both parties, as many Democrats as 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
 The editorial did, however, hit on the real problem when you stated, "You have 
tremendous energy, an enormous appetite for the big issues . . . and an obvious 
desire to make this country better." The problem is the President's ideology is 
to take us on the road to Marxist socialism, and not only Congress but the 
citizens understand that and will continue to stand against his policies, which 
take us in that direction.  
</P>
<P>
 J. BROOKS McNEILL 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles 
</P>
<P>
 * Thank you for the encouragement for President Clinton. I was ready to cancel 
my subscription because your paper is so Republican -- now I know better. 
</P>
<P>
 MARGARET TOLEGIAN 
</P>
<P>
 Monterey Park 
</P>
