<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: WESTMINSTER; TEEN FOUND GUILTY IN '93 MALL SHOOTING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANNA CEKOLA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 19-year-old Santa Ana man was found guilty Monday of four counts of 
attempted murder for shooting and seriously wounding a 13-year-old girl last 
summer in front of terrified shoppers at the Westminster Mall. 
</P>
<P>
 Phong Thanh Dang, who was a student at La Quinta High School at the time of 
the July 8, 1993, shooting, sat without expression as a clerk announced the 
verdict of an Orange County Superior Court jury. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to premeditated attempted murder, the jury found him guilty of 
street terrorism and of committing the crime as part of gang involvement. 
</P>
<P>
 Deputy Dist. Atty. David R. LaBahn said Dang had become angry at a group of 
girls, allegedly also gang members, that afternoon at the mall who, among other 
things, had been staring at him. 
</P>
<P>
 "He got angry and went out to his car and got his gun and went back in the 
mall," LaBahn said. 
</P>
<P>
 The prosecutor said Dang fired at least four shots from a second level of the 
mall into a group of youths standing below. 
</P>
<P>
 A 13-year-old girl was struck in the back, while another bullet passed through 
the pant leg of a 15-year-old girl. 
</P>
<P>
 The prosecution contended that two other girls also were in the line of fire. 
</P>
<P>
 Dang testified he was innocent and someone else did the shooting. His lawyer, 
Thomas Avdeef, could not be reached for comment late Monday. ANNA CEKOLA 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
