<HEADLINE>
<P>
APPLY AS IMMIGRANTS, CUBANS TOLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Clinton Administration is advising Cubans who want to come to the United 
States to apply as immigrants, pointing to a huge unfilled quota as an 
incentive. 
</P>
<P>
 So far this year 2,059 Cubans have been accepted as immigrants. Another 2,300 
have gained entry as political refugees -- a channel that is now severely 
restricted. 
</P>
<P>
 Cuba, like most countries, is allocated up to 7% of the worldwide total for 
immigration to the United States, or 27,845. Nearly 25,800 slots are still 
open. 
</P>
<P>
 State Department officials said Monday that only five countries use up their 
quotas -- China, the Dominican Republic, India, Mexico and the Philippines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
